{"author":{"id":"c4712575109c327bdd55aba22ffc85056a57c52d1f733268a7aaae0da808160e"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1506964848,"nonce":"7Y2hOI865hHaM09cAcoLK3QoQUU=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUyNjIxNTkwMzU=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/1501","origin":"github"},"title":"macs2 should be able to take many treatment files and a single control file.","message":"Hello, \nI've been working on this issue with @mvdbeek|:\n\nThe macs2 callpeak tool in this repo works in two scenarios: when you have 1 treatment file and 1 control file, or when you have a collection of treatment files and control files of the same length. Both these use cases make sense for ChIPseq data (which is what macs was originally developed for) but for ATACseq, which many use macs for as well, it is common to use a single control file for many treatment files. \n\nWhen I put this in my workflow editor: \n\n\u003cimg width=\"539\" alt=\"screen shot 2017-10-02 at 1 14 32 pm\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2761597/31089887-b4efa7d2-a773-11e7-9d7a-55d5aaed175b.png\"\u003e\n\nMacs outputs a single file: peaks using the first treatment file in the collection and the control file -- none of the other treatment files is used, they're all ignored. \n\nVisually, if I have dataset collection [a, b, c, d, e, f, g] and control file [H], I get the results of callpeak(a, H) and nothing else. I'd like to be instead getting [callpeak(a, H), callpeak(b, H), callpeak(c, H), callpeak(d, H), ...] in a collection. \n\nCan we change the macs tool to operate this way?","files":null}]}